Response: NA; we didn't have any changes

Reading Hospital BPCI Advanced care redesign activities continue to be driven by system-level Clinical Effectiveness Teams (CETs) focused on redesigning clinical workflows across the acute and post-acute care settings by service line for each episode selected. The CETs are composed of physicians, nurses, ancillary staff, hospital administrators, and post-acute care providers. Each CET focuses on areas within the continuum of care, closely considering and implementing initiatives built on evidence-based medicine, beneficiary/caregiver engagement, quality and coordination of care, and care transitions.
NA; we are a Non-Convener Participant

Reading Hospital (RH) has been engaged in Medicare-based NPRA since the inception of the CJR program on April 1, 2016, as it was selected as a mandatory participating hospital. RH has gained valuable experience in partnering with its independent orthopedic surgeons to share the NPRA savings and believes that such an arrangement has helped facilitate greater alignment between the physicians and the hospital. RH will utilize these proven processes and policies with other service lines as it engages with physicians in new CMS bundled payment programs.
NA; we don't participate in ICS Sharing

Shared Repayment Amounts associated with BPCI Advanced will be managed and monitored through the Funds Flow CET utilizing processes and procedures that have been in place and vetted through Reading Hospital's CJR experience.

Reading Hospital has engaged ECG Management Consultants for BPCI Advanced implementation support. As part of this engagement, ECG maintains a library of all documents and conveys key activities and timelines to the Tower Health Steering Committee and ensures that knowledge is dispersed throughout the organization. In addition, Tower Health is in the process of hiring a BPCI Advanced Coordinator who will oversee implementation activities throughout the system and serve as a day to day contact.

There have been no unexpected positive or negative outcomes. Positive outcomes have been associated with a multidisciplinary review of current design of internal process of care and subsequent re-design to improve patient throughput, access to care, assessment and treatment. Improvements have also been recognized through the development of a robust transition of care program led by trained care navigators. The care navigators use condition-specific questionnaires to interview patients within 48 hours of hospital discharge.  Care navigators also act as liaisons between the patient and providers as indicated. In addition, we have created internal reports to monitor the required quality metrics as well as additional metrics identified during process re-design. The internal information has provided monthly data as an indicator of successful intervention or the need to re-examine the process to achieve the desired outcome.

Development of patient registries as a way of identifying patients in the BPCI-A bundles. Regularly scheduled operational meeting evaluating developed clinical pathways. Quality dashboards and regular meetings reviewing quality metrics and development of actions as necessary.

Quarterly submission of the FAL and QPP has proven to be burdensome, especially since CMS have been delayed in sending out the FAiL reports. We find ourselves having to reconcile up to three different lists at a time. Given that up to 400 physicians have been eligible to participate as NPRA Sharing Partners it has taken a lot of time to submit correct documentation.

In addition to the burden of the quarterly FAL and QPP submissions, we continue to recommend that CMS consider the burden placed on providers. For example, CMS often requires a quick turnaround, but is often delayed in providing correct materials/data.
NA; we didn't have any changes

Each of our high priority care redesign interventions were linked to thecompletion of the eFusion Care Navigation software platform. eFusion iscurrently functional and continues to evolve concurrent with model anduser needs. As such, each of the high priority care redesigninterventions has been achieved in the time frame indicated in the CRP.
We have no concerns regarding implementation of Care Redesign Interventions.Each general intervention is proceeding as expected. No particular barriershave been identified.
The only challenge in meeting CEHRT requirements is identifying the correctversion of EHR software that qualifies based on the lengthy available listings.
The challenge is the availability of obtaining documentation from episode initiators in atimely manner.

We believe it is important for a Participant, especially a Convener Participant,to take on risk. Most Episode Initiators, regardless of whether they are an ACH or PGP, are risk-averse and not willing to take on risk in a new endeavor that they do not completely understand. The key consideration for taking on risk is dependent on accurate data and informed decision making.

All information on shared repayment amounts is derived from both monthly andreconciliation data reports. Overall performance is assessed monthly to predictanticipated shared repayment or reconciliation amounts. These predictions areshared with each Episode Initiator accordingly.

We continuously prepare current staff for advancement to management roles asa succession plan for when individuals may depart the organization. In addition,we continuously search for new hires to expand the breadth and depth of ourorganization.

We continuously monitor Episode Initiator procedure, processes, and trends tooptimize model performance while also looking for the generation of untendedconsequences. Individualized reports and performance improvement plans areroutinely generated to address performance related issues.

A challenge we have identified is the inability to have a more automatedresponse/document submission system. Having to access each BPIDindividually without an available reference point to indicate those which havebeen completed is excessively time consuming, especially with multipleEpisode Initiators.
